  "prompt": "How is WhatsApp able to show the blurred image even after deleting the original copy from the gallery?",
  "response": "WhatsApp uses a feature that allows users to send images and videos from their devices without actually sending the original file directly, which can lead to the appearance of blurred images even after the original has been deleted from the device's gallery. Here\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Image Files**: When you send an image through WhatsApp, the app creates a compressed version of the image to send. This is often a lower-quality version, which might appear blurred if viewed in a larger format.\n\n2. **Storage on Server**: WhatsApp temporarily stores images on its servers, and these images can be accessed by recipients even if the original file on the sender's device has been deleted. However, these files are typically kept for only a limited time.\n\n3. **Media Visibility**: Even if you delete the original image from your gallery, WhatsApp maintains a cached version in its own storage space. As long as the cached version exists, it can show the image or a preview of it.\n\n4. **Pending Downloads**: If you delete an image after sending it while it\u2019s still pending download (meaning the recipient has not yet downloaded it), the original image can still be accessed temporarily until the download is completed or the cache is cleared.\n\n5. **Media Settings**: In some cases, if you have settings enabled for media auto-download, WhatsApp may store a copy of the image in its own directory, which wouldn't be affected by deletions from the gallery.\n\nOverall, the combination of image compression, temporary server storage, and app caching allows WhatsApp to display images even after the originals are deleted from your device's gallery.",
